{"title_page": "Adachi Station", "text_new": "{{short description|Railway station in Nihonmatsu, Fukushima Prefecture, Japan}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name        = Adachi Station\n| native_name = \u5b89\u9054\u99c5\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| type        = \n| image       = Jr-adachist.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Adachi Station in April 2016\n| other_name  = \n| address     = 5 Aburai Furuyashiki, Nihonmatsu-shi, Fukushima-ken 969-1404\n| country     = Japan\n| map_type    = Japan Fukushima Prefecture#Japan\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37.6117|N|140.4658|E|type:railwaystation_region:JP|display=inline, title}}\n| operator    = [[File:JR logo (east).svg|20px]] [[JR East]]\n| line        = {{Colorbull|MediumSeaGreen}} [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| platforms   = 2 side platforms\n| tracks      = 2\n| distance    = 254.5 km from {{STN|Tokyo}} \n| connections = \n| structure   = \n| code        = \n| status      = Staffed \n| website     = {{official|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=63}}\n| opened      = 11 July 1917\n| closed      = \n| former      =  \n| passengers  = 818 daily\n| pass_year   = FY2016\n| services    = \n| map_type    = Japan Fukushima Prefecture#Japan   \n| map_dot_label       = Adachi Station\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Adachi Station'''|\u5b89\u9054\u99c5|Adachi-eki}} is a [[railway station]] in the city of [[Nihonmatsu, Fukushima|Nihonmatsu]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]], Japan operated by [[East Japan Railway Company]] (JR East). \n\n==Lines==\nAdachi Station is served by the [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]], and is located 254.5 kilometers from the official starting point of the line at {{STN|Tokyo}}. \n\n==Station layout==\nThe station has one [[island platform]] connected to the station building by a footbridge. The station is staffed.\n\n===Platforms===\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=1|first=2|name= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN| Fukushima|Fukushima}}}}\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=2|first=3|nidx= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|K\u014driyama|Fukushima}}}}\n\n==Adjacent stations==\n{{J-railservice start}}\n{{J-route|route=T\u014dhoku Main Line|col=MediumSeaGreen|f=w}}\n{{J-rserv|service=-|previous={{STN|Nihonmatsu}}|next={{STN|Matsukawa}}}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==History==\nAdachi Station opened on July 11, 1917. The station was absorbed into the JR East network upon the privatization of the [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) on April 1, 1987. \n\n==Passenger statistics==\nIn fiscal 2018, the station was used by an average of 787 passengers daily (boarding passengers only).<ref name=\"jreast2018stats\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jreast.co.jp/passenger/2018_06.html|script-title=ja: \u5404\u99c5\u306e\u4e57\u8eca\u4eba\u54e1 (2018\u5e74\u5ea6)|trans-title=Station passenger figures (Fiscal 2018)|year= 2019|publisher= East Japan Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|accessdate= 11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding area==\n*Adachi Post Office\n*Adachi Chamber of Commerce\n*former Adachi Town Hall\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|4}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Japan]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=63}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tohoku Main Line}}\n\n[[Category:Stations of East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Fukushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Nihonmatsu, Fukushima]]\n\n{{Fukushima-railstation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Railway station in Nihonmatsu, Fukushima Prefecture, Japan}}\n{{Refimprove|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox station\n| name        = Adachi Station\n| native_name = \u5b89\u9054\u99c5\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| type        = \n| image       = Jr-adachist.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Adachi Station in April 2016\n| other_name  = \n| address     = 5 Aburai Furuyashiki, Nihonmatsu-shi, Fukushima-ken 969-1404\n| country     = Japan\n| map_type    = Japan Fukushima Prefecture#Japan\n| coordinates = {{Coord|37.6117|N|140.4658|E|type:railwaystation_region:JP|display=inline, title}}\n| operator    = [[File:JR logo (east).svg|20px]] [[JR East]]\n| line        = {{Colorbull|MediumSeaGreen}} [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n| platforms   = 2 side platforms\n| tracks      = 2\n| distance    = 254.5 km from {{STN|Tokyo}} \n| connections = \n| structure   = \n| code        = \n| status      = Staffed \n| website     = {{official|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=63}}\n| opened      = 11 July 1917\n| closed      = \n| former      =  \n| passengers  = 818 daily\n| pass_year   = FY2016\n| services    = \n| map_type    = Japan Fukushima Prefecture#Japan   \n| map_dot_label       = Adachi Station\n \n{{nihongo|'''Adachi Station'''|\u5b89\u9054\u99c5|Adachi-eki}} is a [[railway station]] in the city of [[Nihonmatsu, Fukushima|Nihonmatsu]], [[Fukushima Prefecture]], Japan operated by [[East Japan Railway Company]] (JR East). \n\n==Lines==\nAdachi Station is served by the [[T\u014dhoku Main Line]], and is located 254.5 kilometers from the official starting point of the line at {{STN|Tokyo}}. \n\n==Station layout==\nThe station has one [[island platform]] connected to the station building by a footbridge. The station is staffed.\n\n===Platforms===\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=1|first=2|name= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN| Fukushima|Fukushima}}}}\n{{ja-rail-line|pfn=2|first=3|nidx= T\u014dhoku Main Line |linecol=MediumSeaGreen|dir= for {{STN|K\u014driyama|Fukushima}}}}\n\n==Adjacent stations==\n{{J-railservice start}}\n{{J-route|route=T\u014dhoku Main Line|col=MediumSeaGreen|f=w}}\n{{J-rserv|service=-|previous={{STN|Nihonmatsu}}|next={{STN|Matsukawa}}}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n==History==\nAdachi Station opened on July 11, 1917. The station was absorbed into the JR East network upon the privatization of the [[Japanese National Railways]] (JNR) on April 1, 1987. \n\n==Passenger statistics==\nIn fiscal 2018, the station was used by an average of 787 passengers daily (boarding passengers only).<ref name=\"jreast2018stats\">{{cite web |url= http://www.jreast.co.jp/passenger/2018_06.html|script-title=ja: \u5404\u99c5\u306e\u4e57\u8eca\u4eba\u54e1 (2018\u5e74\u5ea6)|trans-title=Station passenger figures (Fiscal 2018)|year= 2019|publisher= East Japan Railway Company|location= Japan|language= Japanese|accessdate= 11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding area==\n*Adachi Post Office\n*Adachi Chamber of Commerce\n*former Adachi Town Hall\n*{{jct|country=JPN|Route|4}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of railway stations in Japan]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official|1=http://www.jreast.co.jp/estation/station/info.aspx?StationCd=63}} {{in lang|ja}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tohoku Main Line}}\n\n[[Category:Stations of East Japan Railway Company]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Fukushima Prefecture]]\n[[Category:T\u014dhoku Main Line]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:Nihonmatsu, Fukushima]]\n\n{{Fukushima-railstation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MChew", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adachi_Station"}
{"title_page": "Dilraj Singh Bhunder", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder|\n|name          = Dilraj Singh Bhunder\n|native_name   = \n|image         = Dilraj Singh Bhunder.jpg\n|residence     = \n|term          = 2017 - Present\n|office       = [[Member of Legislative Assembly]], [[Punjab]]\n|constituency = Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District, Punjab|Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n|term2        = 2012 - 2017\n|office2      = [[Vice President]], Youth Wing, [[Shiromani Akali Dal]]\n|term3        = 2008 - 2012\n|office3       = [[Zila Parishad]] [[Chairman]]\n|constituency3 = Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n|party         = [[Shiromani Akali Dal]]\n|spouse        = Veerpal Kaur\n|relatives     = Balraj Singh Bhunder (Brother)\n|father        = [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder]]\n|mother        = Balwant Kaur\n}}\n'''Dilraj Singh Bhunder''' is an Indian politician, currently a member of the [[Punjab Legislative Assembly]] or the [[Punjab Vidhan Sabha]]. He is the son of Sardar [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder]], who is currently a member of the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the [[Parliament of India]], from the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Balwinder Singh Bhunder|date=2020-04-18|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Balwinder_Singh_Bhunder&oldid=951785435|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Dilraj is a member of the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. He is a former [[Vice President]] of Youth Wing [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. Dilraj is an engineering graduate from [[Punjab Engineering College]], [[Chandigarh]].\n\n== Early Life ==\nDilraj was born on 11 January 1969 in [[Bathinda]], [[Punjab]], to Sardar [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder|Balwinder Singh Bhunde]]<nowiki/>r and Shrimati Balwant Kaur. He spent his early life living and schooling in Chandigarh. Dilraj had a strong interest in engineering and science since his childhood. He was an avid athlete growing up and competed in 5 national Volleyball games and was the youngest caption to ever had to play in nationals.\n\n== Biography ==\nDilraj married Veerpal Kaur in 1994. Dilraj's deceased brother, [https://en.gyaanipedia.co.in/wiki/Balraj_Singh_Bhunder Balraj Singh Bhundar] was previously an important political figure for the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2008 to 2012, Dilraj became the [[Zila Parishad]] [[Chairman]], [[Mansa]]. From 2012 to 2017, he was the [[Vice President]] of the Youth Wing for the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. Dilraj was elected as a a member of the [[Punjab Legislative Assembly]] or the [[Punjab Vidhan Sabha]] from Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]].\n\nDilraj has been actively been a part of many committees including the Committee on Petitions of Punjab Vidhan Sabha, Committee of Local Bodies & Panchayati Raj Institution of Punjab Vidhan Sabha, and the Library Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://punjabassembly.nic.in/index.php/members/detail/215|title=Members|website=punjabassembly.nic.in|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder|\n|name          = Dilraj Singh Bhunder\n|native_name   = \n|image         = Dilraj Singh Bhunder.jpg\n|residence     = \n|term          = 2017 - Present\n|office       = [[Member of Legislative Assembly]], [[Punjab]]\n|constituency = Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District, Punjab|Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n|term2        = 2012 - 2017\n|office2      = [[Vice President]], Youth Wing, [[Shiromani Akali Dal]]\n|term3        = 2008 - 2012\n|office3       = [[Zila Parishad]] [[Chairman]]\n|constituency3 = Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n|party         = [[Shiromani Akali Dal]]\n|spouse        = Veerpal Kaur\n|relatives     = Balraj Singh Bhunder (Brother)\n|father        = [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder]]\n|mother        = Balwant Kaur\n}}\n'''Dilraj Singh Bhunder''' is an Indian politician, currently a member of the [[Punjab Legislative Assembly]] or the [[Punjab Vidhan Sabha]]. He is the son of Sardar [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder]], who is currently a member of the [[Rajya Sabha]], the upper house of the [[Parliament of India]], from the state of [[Punjab, India|Punjab]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Balwinder Singh Bhunder|date=2020-04-18|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Balwinder_Singh_Bhunder&oldid=951785435|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Dilraj is a member of the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. He is a former [[Vice President]] of Youth Wing [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. Dilraj is an engineering graduate from [[Punjab Engineering College]], [[Chandigarh]].\n\n== Early Life ==\nDilraj was born on 11 January 1969 in [[Bathinda]], [[Punjab]], to Sardar [[Balwinder Singh Bhunder|Balwinder Singh Bhunde]]<nowiki/>r and Shrimati Balwant Kaur. He spent his early life living and schooling in Chandigarh. Dilraj had a strong interest in engineering and science since his childhood. He was an avid athlete growing up and competed in 5 national Volleyball games and was the youngest caption to ever had to play in nationals.\n\n== Biography ==\nDilraj married Veerpal Kaur in 1994. Dilraj's deceased brother, Balraj Singh Bhundar was previously an important political figure for the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party.\n\n== Career ==\nFrom 2008 to 2012, Dilraj became the [[Zila Parishad]] [[Chairman]], [[Mansa]]. From 2012 to 2017, he was the [[Vice President]] of the Youth Wing for the [[Shiromani Akali Dal]] party. Dilraj was elected as a a member of the [[Punjab Legislative Assembly]] or the [[Punjab Vidhan Sabha]] from Sardulgarh, [[Mansa District]], [[Punjab]], [[India]].\n\nDilraj has been actively been a part of many committees including the Committee on Petitions of Punjab Vidhan Sabha, Committee of Local Bodies & Panchayati Raj Institution of Punjab Vidhan Sabha, and the Library Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://punjabassembly.nic.in/index.php/members/detail/215|title=Members|website=punjabassembly.nic.in|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "AutonomousUser", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added brother's link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dilraj_Singh_Bhunder"}
{"title_page": "Joginder Singh (soldier)", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Subedar Joginder Singh|the biography film|Subedar Joginder Singh (film)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Subedar]]\n| name          = Joginder Singh Sahnan\n| honorific_suffix = [[Param Vir Chakra|PVC]]\n| image         = Joginder_SIngh_PVC.jpg\n| image_size    = 250px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1921|09|28|df=y}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1962|10|23|1921|09|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = Mahla kalan, [[Moga district]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_place   = [[Bum La Pass]], [[North-East Frontier Agency]], [[India]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = {{Flag|British India}}<br>{{Flag|India}}\n| branch        = {{Army|British India}}<br>{{Army|India}}\n| serviceyears  = 1936\u20131962\n| rank          = [[File:Subedar - Risaldar of the Indian Army.svg|24px]] [[Subedar]]\n| servicenumber = JC-4547{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}}\n| unit          = 1st battalion, [[Sikh Regiment]]\n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[Second World War]]<br>[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]]<br>[[Sino-Indian War]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = [[File:Param-Vir-Chakra-ribbon.svg|32px]] [[Param Vir Chakra]]\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n}}\n[[Subedar]] '''Joginder Singh Sahnan''', [[Param Vir Chakra|PVC]] (28 September 1921 &ndash; 23 October 1962), was an [[Indian Army]] soldier who posthumously received India's highest military gallantry award, the [[Param Vir Chakra]]. Singh joined the [[British Indian Army]] in 1936, and served in the 1st battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]]. During the 1962 [[Sino-Indian War]], he was commanding a platoon at the [[Bum La Pass]] in the [[North-East Frontier Agency]]. Though heavily outnumbered, he led his troops against a Chinese assault and defended his post until he was wounded and captured. Singh died from his injuries while in Chinese custody.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html |title=The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh - Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962|author=Maninder Dabas|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJoginder Singh was born on 28 September 1921 in Mahalakalan, [[Moga district]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]. He spent his childhood in the same village. His father Sher Singh Sahnan belonged to an agricultural [[Saini]] Sikh family which had relocated to Mahalakalan from the village Munak Kalan (Often pronounced as Munaka) in [[Hoshiarpur district]].<ref name=\"Prof. Nanua\">Saini Jagat: Utpati Ate Vikas, pp 121, Prof. Surjit Singh Nanuan, Manjota Publications, Patiala, 2008</ref><ref>Tributes paid to Subedar Joginder Singh Saini, October 23, 2017, Daily Ajit (Punjabi Edition), Jalandhar</ref><ref name=\"Tribune_community_background\">\"He became the second Saini Sikh to get the PVC after Capt Gurbachan Singh Salaria, who earned the award posthumously leading a Khukri charge in December 1961 at Katanga, Congo, while on a UN Mission \",When the will became a weapon, The Tribune, Sunday, August 05, 2018| url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/spectrum/when-the-will-became-a-weapon/572352.html</ref> His mother was Bibi Krishan Kaur Bhela. Joginder Singh married Bibi Gurdyal Kaur Banga, who was from a [[Saini]] family in the village Kothay Rara Singh, near [[Kotkapura]]. He went to primary school in Nathu Ala village and went to middle school in Daroli village.<ref name=\"Prof. Nanua\"/> He decided to join the army, considering that it would give him an \"identity and purpose\".{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}}\n\n== Military career ==\nOn joining the [[British Indian Army]], Singh was posted to the 1st battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]] (1 Sikh) on 28 September 1936.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}}<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\">{{cite web|author1=Maninder Dabas|title=The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html|website=Indiatimes|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102223824/https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref> After joining the army, he identified his interest in education, and soon passed the Army Education Examination. He was subsequently appointed as the Unit Education Instructor.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}} He served in the [[Second World War]] on the [[Burma Campaign|Burma front]], and in [[Srinagar]] during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947|Indo-Pakistani War of 1947\u20131948]].<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n===Sino-India War===\n{{main|Sino-Indian War}}\nThere had long been disagreement between India and China over disputed borders in the Himalaya region. To counter the increasing Chinese intrusions into disputed territory, then [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] asked for strategies for dealing with them. However, the proposal put forward by the [[Indian Army]] was rejected. Instead, he approved a plan proposed by a bureaucrat called the \"Forward Policy\". This called for the establishment of a number of small posts facing the Chinese. Due the severe rise in public criticism against Chinese intrusions, Nehru implemented the \"Forward Policy\" against the advice of the army.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=73}} The army's concern was that the Chinese had geographical advantage. Additionally, maintaining numerous small posts would be untenable if the Chinese superior forces attacked. This was ruled out by Nehru who believed the Chinese would not attack. But the Chinese did, initiating the Sino-India War.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=74}}\n\n====Battle at Bum La====\nOn 9 September 1962, then [[Defence Minister of India]] [[Krishna Menon]] made a decision to evict the Chinese troops south of Thala Ridge. This decision was endorsed by Nehru, who was in [[London]] to attend the [[Commonwealth Prime Ministers' Conference]]. Subsequently, the [[7th Indian Infantry Brigade|7th Infantry Brigade]], which included 1 Sikh, was ordered to move to [[Namka Chu]], which was considered as militarily unsound and an advantageous ground for the Chinese. This move was strongly criticized by the [[Indian media]], who publicized it with \"sensational headlines\", arguing India's military offensive capability.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}}\n\nThe Chinese, aware of these developments, attacked the unprepared Indian post at Namka Chu. Though the Indian troops resisted the attack, they took heavy casualties due to inadequate ammunition and weak communication lines. Soon after the attack, the Chinese advanced to [[Tawang]]. Midway they encountered an Indian post at the [[Bum La Pass]], held by a platoon of 20 men from 1 Sikh.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}}<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" /> The post was under the command of Singh, now a [[subedar]].{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}} The Chinese attacked the post in three waves, each comprising 200 men.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}} Though the initial two attacks were repelled successfully, by that time, the platoon was depleted to half of its original strength. Singh was also wounded, but refused evacuation. Soon the ammunition was exhausted, and the survivors were only left with their [[bayonet]]s.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=70}}\n\nThe Sikh soldiers then charged towards the Chinese, shouting the war cry ''Waheguru Ji Ka Khalsa, Waheguru Ji Ki Fateh''.{{efn|{{lang-en|Hail the [[Khalsa]] who belongs to the Lord God! Hail the Lord God to whom belongs the victory}}.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=59}}}} The Chinese lines were scattered at this sight and many were bayoneted. Due to heavy numbers and superior weapons, the Chinese were able to withstand the last charge by Singh and his remaining soldiers.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=70}} Before Singh was overpowered and captured by the Chinese, he single-handedly killed several Chinese soldiers with his bayonet. He later succumbed to his injuries and died in Chinese captivity.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n=== Param Vir Chakra ===\nThough being heavily outnumbered, Singh led his men, and kept their morale up, in the face of enemy. For his action of gallantry on 23 October 1962, he was awarded the Param Vir Chakra.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=59}} The citation reads:\n{{Quotation|\nSubedar Joginder Singh was the commander of a platoon of the Sikh Regiment holding a defensive position at a ridge near Tongpen La in NEFA. At 0530 hours on 23 October 1962, the Chinese opened a very heavy attack on the Bum la axis with the intention of breaking through to Towang. The leading battalion of the enemy attacked the ridge in three waves, each about 200 strong. Subedar Joginder Singh and his men mowed down the first wave, and the enemy was temporarily halted by the heavy losses it suffered. With in a few minutes, a second wave came over and was dealt with similarly. But the platoon had, by then, lost half its men. Subedar Joginder Singh was wounded in the thigh but refused to be evacuated. Under his inspiring leadership the platoon stubbornly held its ground and would not withdraw. Meanwhile the position was attacked for the third time. Subedar Joginder Singh himself manned a light machine-gun and shot down a number of the enemy. The Chinese however continued to advance despite heavy losses. When the situation became untenable Subedar Joginder Singh and the few men that were left in the position fixed bayonets and charged the advancing Chinese, bayoneting a number of them before he and his comrades were overpowered. Throughout this action, Subedar joginder Singh displayed devotion to duty, inspiring leadership and bravery of the highest order.|author=[[Gazette of India]] Notification No.68\u2014Press/62|source={{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|pp=70\u201371}}}}\n\nOn hearing the news of Singh's death, his elder daughter died.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}} The Chinese sent his ashes with full military honours to the battalion on 17 May 1963.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" /> The urn was later brought to the Sikh Regimental Centre at [[Meerut]], and eventually handed over to his wife.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n== Other honours ==\n[[File:Subedar Joginder Singh statue at Param Yodha Sthal Delhi.jpg|250px|thumb|Singh's statue at ''Param Yodha Sthal'', [[National War Memorial (India)|National War Memorial]], New Delhi]]\nIn the 1980s, the [[Shipping Corporation of India]] (SCI), a [[Government of India]] enterprise under the aegis of the [[Ministry of Shipping (India)|Ministry of Shipping]], named fifteen of its [[crude oil tanker]]s in honour of the PVC recipients. The tanker MT ''Subedar Joginder Singh, PVC'' was delivered to SCI in 1984, and served for 25 years before being phased out.<ref name=\"Subedar Joginder Singh PVC Ship\">{{cite web|title=Subedar Joginder Singh PVC Ship|url=https://shipping-data.com/ship/subedar-joginder-singh-pvc|website=Shipping Data|publisher=ED Web Consulting|accessdate=21 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042710/https://shipping-data.com/ship/subedar-joginder-singh-pvc|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref> In Singh's honour, a memorial statue has been built near the Office of District Collector in Moga, and a monument has been built at IB Ridge by the Indian Army.<ref name=\"Remembering Param Vir Subedar Joginder Singh and His Extraordinary Tale of Bravery\">{{cite web|author1=Sanchari Pal|title=Remembering Param Vir Subedar Joginder Singh and His Extraordinary Tale of Bravery|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/116778/subedar-joginder-singh-param-vir-chakra-punjab-china-war/|website=The Better India|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=27 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031123/https://www.thebetterindia.com/116778/subedar-joginder-singh-param-vir-chakra-punjab-china-war/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe 2018 [[biopic]] ''[[Subedar Joginder Singh (film)|Subedar Joginder Singh]]'' is based on Singh's life and his action during Sino-Indian War. The lead role was played by Punjabi actor-singer [[Gippy Grewal]].<ref name=\"Gippy Grewal on PVC Subedar Joginder Singh biopic: It\u2019s a massive responsibility to play this national hero\">{{cite web|title=Gippy Grewal on PVC Subedar Joginder Singh biopic: It\u2019s a massive responsibility to play this national hero|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/punjabi-singer-actor-gippy-grewal-set-to-play-pvc-subedar-joginder-singh-in-his-biopic-4798172/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030417/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/punjabi-singer-actor-gippy-grewal-set-to-play-pvc-subedar-joginder-singh-in-his-biopic-4798172/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n[[Joginder Singh (field hockey)|Joginder Singh (field hocke)]]\n\n[[Joginder Singh (field hockey)|y)]]{{refbegin|}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cardozo|first1=Ian|title=Param Vir : our heroes in battle|date=2003|publisher=Lotus Collection|location=New Delhi|pages=|year=|isbn=9788174362629|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Thapliyal|first1=B.C. Chakravorty ; edited by U.P.|title=Stories of heroism|date=1995|publisher=Allied Publishers|location=New Delhi|pages=|year=|isbn=978-81-7023-516-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last=Rawat |first=Rachna Bisht |year=2014 |title=The Brave: Param Vir Chakra Stories |publisher=Penguin Books India Private Limited |isbn=978-01-4342-235-8}}\n*{{citation|first1=Kittu |last1=Reddy|title=Bravest of the Brave: Heroes of the Indian Army|year=2007|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-87100-00-3|language=English}}\n{{Param Vir Chakra recipients}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Joginder}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sikh warriors]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Indian military personnel killed in action]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Param Vir Chakra]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Punjab, India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Subedar Joginder Singh|the biography film|Subedar Joginder Singh (film)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Subedar]]\n| name          = Joginder Singh Sahnan\n| honorific_suffix = [[Param Vir Chakra|PVC]]\n| image         = Joginder_SIngh_PVC.jpg\n| image_size    = 250px\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1921|09|28|df=y}}\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1962|10|23|1921|09|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = Mahla kalan, [[Moga district]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_place   = [[Bum La Pass]], [[North-East Frontier Agency]], [[India]]\n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_name    = \n| allegiance    = [[British India]]<br>India\n| branch        = [[British Indian Army]]<br>[[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1936\u20131962\n| rank          = [[File:Subedar - Risaldar of the Indian Army.svg|24px]] [[Subedar]]\n| servicenumber = JC-4547{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}}\n| unit          = 1st battalion, [[Sikh Regiment]]\n| commands      = \n| battles       = [[Second World War]]<br>[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]]<br>[[Sino-Indian War]]\n| battles_label = \n| awards        = [[File:Param-Vir-Chakra-ribbon.svg|32px]] [[Param Vir Chakra]]\n| relations     = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n}}\n[[Subedar]] '''Joginder Singh Sahnan''', [[Param Vir Chakra|PVC]] (28 September 1921 &ndash; 23 October 1962), was an [[Indian Army]] soldier who posthumously received India's highest military gallantry award, the [[Param Vir Chakra]]. Singh joined the [[British Indian Army]] in 1936, and served in the 1st battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]]. During the 1962 [[Sino-Indian War]], he was commanding a platoon at the [[Bum La Pass]] in the [[North-East Frontier Agency]]. Though heavily outnumbered, he led his troops against a Chinese assault and defended his post until he was wounded and captured. Singh died from his injuries while in Chinese custody.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html |title=The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh - Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962|author=Maninder Dabas|date=6 July 2017|accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJoginder Singh was born on 28 September 1921 in Mahalakalan, [[Moga district]], [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]], [[British Raj|British India]]. He spent his childhood in the same village. His father Sher Singh Sahnan belonged to an agricultural [[Saini]] Sikh family which had relocated to Mahalakalan from the village Munak Kalan (Often pronounced as Munaka) in [[Hoshiarpur district]].<ref name=\"Prof. Nanua\">Saini Jagat: Utpati Ate Vikas, pp 121, Prof. Surjit Singh Nanuan, Manjota Publications, Patiala, 2008</ref><ref>Tributes paid to Subedar Joginder Singh Saini, October 23, 2017, Daily Ajit (Punjabi Edition), Jalandhar</ref><ref name=\"Tribune_community_background\">\"He became the second Saini Sikh to get the PVC after Capt Gurbachan Singh Salaria, who earned the award posthumously leading a Khukri charge in December 1961 at Katanga, Congo, while on a UN Mission \",When the will became a weapon, The Tribune, Sunday, August 05, 2018| url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/spectrum/when-the-will-became-a-weapon/572352.html</ref> His mother was Bibi Krishan Kaur Bhela. Joginder Singh married Bibi Gurdyal Kaur Banga, who was from a [[Saini]] family in the village Kothay Rara Singh, near [[Kotkapura]]. He went to primary school in Nathu Ala village and went to middle school in Daroli village.<ref name=\"Prof. Nanua\"/> He decided to join the army, considering that it would give him an \"identity and purpose\".{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}}\n\n== Military career ==\nOn joining the [[British Indian Army]], Singh was posted to the 1st battalion of the [[Sikh Regiment]] (1 Sikh) on 28 September 1936.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}}<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\">{{cite web|author1=Maninder Dabas|title=The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html|website=Indiatimes|publisher=Times Internet|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=18 August 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102223824/https://www.indiatimes.com/news/the-story-of-subedar-joginder-singh-who-crushed-waves-of-chinese-attacks-at-bum-la-in-tawang-in-1962_-260151.html|archivedate=2 November 2017}}</ref> After joining the army, he identified his interest in education, and soon passed the Army Education Examination. He was subsequently appointed as the Unit Education Instructor.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}} He served in the [[Second World War]] on the [[Burma Campaign|Burma front]], and in [[Srinagar]] during the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947|Indo-Pakistani War of 1947\u20131948]].<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n===Sino-India War===\n{{main|Sino-Indian War}}\nThere had long been disagreement between India and China over disputed borders in the Himalaya region. To counter the increasing Chinese intrusions into disputed territory, then [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] asked for strategies for dealing with them. However, the proposal put forward by the [[Indian Army]] was rejected. Instead, he approved a plan proposed by a bureaucrat called the \"Forward Policy\". This called for the establishment of a number of small posts facing the Chinese. Due the severe rise in public criticism against Chinese intrusions, Nehru implemented the \"Forward Policy\" against the advice of the army.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=73}} The army's concern was that the Chinese had geographical advantage. Additionally, maintaining numerous small posts would be untenable if the Chinese superior forces attacked. This was ruled out by Nehru who believed the Chinese would not attack. But the Chinese did, initiating the Sino-India War.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=74}}\n\n====Battle at Bum La====\nOn 9 September 1962, then [[Defence Minister of India]] [[Krishna Menon]] made a decision to evict the Chinese troops south of Thala Ridge. This decision was endorsed by Nehru, who was in [[London]] to attend the [[Commonwealth Prime Ministers' Conference]]. Subsequently, the [[7th Indian Infantry Brigade|7th Infantry Brigade]], which included 1 Sikh, was ordered to move to [[Namka Chu]], which was considered as militarily unsound and an advantageous ground for the Chinese. This move was strongly criticized by the [[Indian media]], who publicized it with \"sensational headlines\", arguing India's military offensive capability.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}}\n\nThe Chinese, aware of these developments, attacked the unprepared Indian post at Namka Chu. Though the Indian troops resisted the attack, they took heavy casualties due to inadequate ammunition and weak communication lines. Soon after the attack, the Chinese advanced to [[Tawang]]. Midway they encountered an Indian post at the [[Bum La Pass]], held by a platoon of 20 men from 1 Sikh.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}}<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" /> The post was under the command of Singh, now a [[subedar]].{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=69}} The Chinese attacked the post in three waves, each comprising 200 men.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=58}} Though the initial two attacks were repelled successfully, by that time, the platoon was depleted to half of its original strength. Singh was also wounded, but refused evacuation. Soon the ammunition was exhausted, and the survivors were only left with their [[bayonet]]s.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=70}}\n\nThe Sikh soldiers then charged towards the Chinese, shouting the war cry ''Waheguru Ji Ka Khalsa, Waheguru Ji Ki Fateh''.{{efn|{{lang-en|Hail the [[Khalsa]] who belongs to the Lord God! Hail the Lord God to whom belongs the victory}}.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=59}}}} The Chinese lines were scattered at this sight and many were bayoneted. Due to heavy numbers and superior weapons, the Chinese were able to withstand the last charge by Singh and his remaining soldiers.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=70}} Before Singh was overpowered and captured by the Chinese, he single-handedly killed several Chinese soldiers with his bayonet. He later succumbed to his injuries and died in Chinese captivity.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n=== Param Vir Chakra ===\nThough being heavily outnumbered, Singh led his men, and kept their morale up, in the face of enemy. For his action of gallantry on 23 October 1962, he was awarded the Param Vir Chakra.{{Sfn|Chakravorty|1995|p=59}} The citation reads:\n{{Quotation|\nSubedar Joginder Singh was the commander of a platoon of the Sikh Regiment holding a defensive position at a ridge near Tongpen La in NEFA. At 0530 hours on 23 October 1962, the Chinese opened a very heavy attack on the Bum la axis with the intention of breaking through to Towang. The leading battalion of the enemy attacked the ridge in three waves, each about 200 strong. Subedar Joginder Singh and his men mowed down the first wave, and the enemy was temporarily halted by the heavy losses it suffered. With in a few minutes, a second wave came over and was dealt with similarly. But the platoon had, by then, lost half its men. Subedar Joginder Singh was wounded in the thigh but refused to be evacuated. Under his inspiring leadership the platoon stubbornly held its ground and would not withdraw. Meanwhile the position was attacked for the third time. Subedar Joginder Singh himself manned a light machine-gun and shot down a number of the enemy. The Chinese however continued to advance despite heavy losses. When the situation became untenable Subedar Joginder Singh and the few men that were left in the position fixed bayonets and charged the advancing Chinese, bayoneting a number of them before he and his comrades were overpowered. Throughout this action, Subedar joginder Singh displayed devotion to duty, inspiring leadership and bravery of the highest order.|author=[[Gazette of India]] Notification No.68\u2014Press/62|source={{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|pp=70\u201371}}}}\n\nOn hearing the news of Singh's death, his elder daughter died.{{Sfn|Cardozo|2003|p=72}} The Chinese sent his ashes with full military honours to the battalion on 17 May 1963.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" /> The urn was later brought to the Sikh Regimental Centre at [[Meerut]], and eventually handed over to his wife.<ref name=\"The Story of Subedar Joginder Singh \u2013 Who Crushed Waves Of Chinese Attacks At Bum La In Tawang In 1962\" />\n\n== Other honours ==\n[[File:Subedar Joginder Singh statue at Param Yodha Sthal Delhi.jpg|250px|thumb|Singh's statue at ''Param Yodha Sthal'', [[National War Memorial (India)|National War Memorial]], New Delhi]]\nIn the 1980s, the [[Shipping Corporation of India]] (SCI), a [[Government of India]] enterprise under the aegis of the [[Ministry of Shipping (India)|Ministry of Shipping]], named fifteen of its [[crude oil tanker]]s in honour of the PVC recipients. The tanker MT ''Subedar Joginder Singh, PVC'' was delivered to SCI in 1984, and served for 25 years before being phased out.<ref name=\"Subedar Joginder Singh PVC Ship\">{{cite web|title=Subedar Joginder Singh PVC Ship|url=https://shipping-data.com/ship/subedar-joginder-singh-pvc|website=Shipping Data|publisher=ED Web Consulting|accessdate=21 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201042710/https://shipping-data.com/ship/subedar-joginder-singh-pvc|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref> In Singh's honour, a memorial statue has been built near the Office of District Collector in Moga, and a monument has been built at IB Ridge by the Indian Army.<ref name=\"Remembering Param Vir Subedar Joginder Singh and His Extraordinary Tale of Bravery\">{{cite web|author1=Sanchari Pal|title=Remembering Param Vir Subedar Joginder Singh and His Extraordinary Tale of Bravery|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/116778/subedar-joginder-singh-param-vir-chakra-punjab-china-war/|website=The Better India|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=27 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031123/https://www.thebetterindia.com/116778/subedar-joginder-singh-param-vir-chakra-punjab-china-war/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe 2018 [[biopic]] ''[[Subedar Joginder Singh (film)|Subedar Joginder Singh]]'' is based on Singh's life and his action during Sino-Indian War. The lead role was played by Punjabi actor-singer [[Gippy Grewal]].<ref name=\"Gippy Grewal on PVC Subedar Joginder Singh biopic: It\u2019s a massive responsibility to play this national hero\">{{cite web|title=Gippy Grewal on PVC Subedar Joginder Singh biopic: It\u2019s a massive responsibility to play this national hero|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/punjabi-singer-actor-gippy-grewal-set-to-play-pvc-subedar-joginder-singh-in-his-biopic-4798172/|website=The Indian Express|accessdate=21 November 2017|date=16 August 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201030417/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/punjabi-singer-actor-gippy-grewal-set-to-play-pvc-subedar-joginder-singh-in-his-biopic-4798172/|archivedate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n[[Joginder Singh (field hockey)|Joginder Singh (field hocke)]]\n\n[[Joginder Singh (field hockey)|y)]]{{refbegin|}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cardozo|first1=Ian|title=Param Vir : our heroes in battle|date=2003|publisher=Lotus Collection|location=New Delhi|pages=|year=|isbn=9788174362629|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Thapliyal|first1=B.C. Chakravorty ; edited by U.P.|title=Stories of heroism|date=1995|publisher=Allied Publishers|location=New Delhi|pages=|year=|isbn=978-81-7023-516-3}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation|last=Rawat |first=Rachna Bisht |year=2014 |title=The Brave: Param Vir Chakra Stories |publisher=Penguin Books India Private Limited |isbn=978-01-4342-235-8}}\n*{{citation|first1=Kittu |last1=Reddy|title=Bravest of the Brave: Heroes of the Indian Army|year=2007|publisher=Prabhat Prakashan|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-87100-00-3|language=English}}\n{{Param Vir Chakra recipients}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Joginder}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sikh warriors]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Indian military personnel killed in action]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Param Vir Chakra]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Punjab, India]]\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joginder_Singh_(soldier)"}
{"title_page": "Human rights issues during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], human rights violations including censorship, discrimination, arbitrary detention, xenophobia were reported from different parts of the world. [[Amnesty International]] has responded that \"Human rights violations hinder, rather than facilitate, responses to public health emergencies, and undercut their efficiency.\"<ref name=\"amnesty7\">{{cite web |title=Here are seven ways the coronavirus affects human rights |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/02/explainer-seven-ways-the-coronavirus-affects-human-rights/ |website=www.amnesty.org |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The World Health Organization has stated that stay-at-home measures for slowing down the pandemic must not be done at the expense of human rights.<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 - 13 April 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19--13-april-2020 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=www.who.int |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\n{{see also|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Censorship and police responses}}\n===China===\nThe government of China enforced early censorship to suppress information about the coronavirus, and the dangers it poses to public health.<ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite news |title=How the coronavirus has deepened human rights abuses in China |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/cloneofcloneofcoronavirus-deepened-human-right-200312074518781.html |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref name=\"guardianchina\">{{cite news |last1=Eve |first1=Frances |title=China's reaction to the coronavirus violates human rights Frances Eve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/02/chinas-reaction-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak-violates-human-rights |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=2 February 2020}}</ref> There were criticisms that the epidemic was allowed to spread for weeks before efforts were undertaken to contain the virus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wuhan |first1=About The Author Da ShijiDa Shiji is the penname of a veteran journalist living in the city of |title=The Truth About \"Dramatic Action\" |url=https://chinamediaproject.org/2020/01/27/dramatic-actions/ |website=China Media Project |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> [[Li Wenliang]], a Chinese doctor who alerted his colleagues about coronavirus was censored and then detained for \"spreading false rumors.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yu |first1=Verna |title=Senior Wuhan doctor dies from coronavirus as authorities start to 'round up' patients |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/18/senior-wuhan-doctor-dies-from-coronavirus-as-authorities-start-to-round-up-patients |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 February 2020}}</ref> He succumbed to the infection and later died.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buckley |first1=Chris |last2=Myers |first2=Steven Lee |title=As New Coronavirus Spread, China's Old Habits Delayed Fight |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/01/world/asia/china-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |date=1 February 2020}}</ref> Amnesty International criticized that China's aggressive lobbying of the [[World Health Organization]] involved minimizing of the severity of the outbreak.<ref name=\"amnesty7\"/>\n\n\"[[Plague Inc.]]\", a mobile game that focuses on the simulation of global pandemics was banned by the [[Cyberspace Administration of China]] on the grounds that it had \"illegal content\" and was promptly removed from all Chinese digital stores. Ndemic Creations, the game developer, said that it is unclear whether this was in connection to the coronavirus outbreak but that they plan to work hard to get their game back into Chinese players hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/2020/02/28/plague-inc-removed-chinas-app-store/|title=Plague Inc removed from China App Store|last=Hume|first=Mike|date=|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nAn experienced midwife working [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Poland|during the pandemic in a Polish hospital]] was fired after she published a report on [[Facebook]] on 18 March about the conditions of medical personnel and the hospital in relation to the pandemic. Reports came out afterwards that doctors were being forbidden from providing information to the media. On 25 March 2020, the [[Polish Ombudsman]] [[Adam Bodnar]] informed the Minister of Health that medical staff's freedom of speech and the public's right to know are guaranteed under [[:s:Constitution of the Republic of Poland/Chapter 1|Articles 2]], [[:s:Constitution of the Republic of Poland/Chapter 2|54 and 61 of the Polish Constitution]] and that firing or punishing doctors for informing the public during the pandemic could be a violation of the \"obligatory standards\".<ref name=\"PortPielPoloz_fired\" />\n\nOn 26 March, Poland's secretary of state of the Ministry of Health, {{ill|J\u00f3zefa Szczurek-\u017belazko|pl}}, published a written statement forbidding [[Voivodeships of Poland|voivodeship]] medical consultants from making statements related to the coronavirus unless they first consulted with the Ministry of Health or {{ill|G\u0142\u00f3wny Inspektorat Sanitarny|pl}} (GIS, the national health agency).<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\" /> A doctors' group, ''Porozumieniu Chirurg\u00f3w SKALPEL'', described the order as [[blackmail]] and said that it risked catastrophe.<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\" />\n\n=== Turkmenistan ===\nThe government of Turkmenistan outlawed the word \"Coronavirus\" on media. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/31/turkmenistan-government-outlaws-use-of-word-coronavirus/|title=Turkmenistan government outlaws any mention of the word \u2018coronavirus\u2019\n|date=31 March 2020|work=}}</ref>\n\n=== Social networks ===\nVarious [[social networking service|social networks]] applied anti-spam measures for content posted about SARS-CoV-2 and the pandemic. [[Facebook]] allegedly censored informative content about the virus.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koetsier|first1=John|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnkoetsier/2020/03/17/facebook-deleting-coronavirus-posts-leading-to-charges-of-censorship/#29a970be5962|title=Facebook Deleting Coronavirus Posts, Leading To Charges Of Censorship|date=17 March 2020|work=Forbes|last2=|first2=}}</ref> According to users, posts about the coronavirus from reliable sources of media were blocked and hidden from other users. Facebook claimed a bug was responsible for this, but conspiracies are circulating that this was done deliberately to suppress information.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[YouTube]] demonetized several videos in which the term \"corona\" was used. The demonetization was cited under the rules of sensitive content.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/youtube-reportedly-censors-videos-about-novel-coronavirus-by-removal-or-demonetization-company-says-they-fall-under-%E2%80%9Csensitive-topics%E2%80%9D|title=YouTube reportedly censors videos about novel coronavirus by removal or demonetization, company says they fall under 'sensitive topics'|date=20 March 2020|work=}}</ref>\n\n==Right to health==\nIn China, many patients had to be turned away from hospitals after hours of queuing due to the high number of ill people.<ref name=\"amnesty7\"/> Shortage of testing and treating material were reported.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Qin |first1=Amy |title=Coronavirus Pummels Wuhan, a City Short of Supplies and Overwhelmed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/02/world/asia/china-coronavirus-wuhan.html |work=The New York Times |date=2 February 2020}}</ref> \nDue to the high volume of patient inflow in Italy, doctors were forced to decide on whether or not to treat the elderly, or leave them to die.<ref name = italyhealth>{{cite news |last1=Horowitz |first1=Jason |title=Italy's Health Care System Groans Under Coronavirus \u2014 a Warning to the World |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/12italy-coronavirus-health-care.html |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A photo of a nurse who collapsed due to huge workload in an Italian hospital was widely circulated as a symbol of the overwhelmed system.<ref name = italyhealth/>\n\nIn Libya, the medical situation was worsening amidst the ongoing war, where hospitals were constantly being attacked. In April 2020, the [[United Nations|UN]] humanitarian coordinator for [[Libya]], Yacoub El Hillo confirmed that 27 health facilities have been damaged and 14 close in five weeks. On April 6, UAE-backed forces of Khalifa Haftar launched a [[Grad rocket]] attack against the Al-[[Khadra'|Khadra]] General Hospital and damaged the 400-bed facility, where 300 patients, including two COVID-19 patients, were being treated. The attack was condemned as a violation of [[international humanitarian law]] by Yacoub El Hillo.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/04/1061272|title=Course of coronavirus pandemic across Libya, depends on silencing the guns|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=UN News|date=7 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/libya-war-escalates-health-care-system-crumbles|title=Libya War Escalates as Health Care System Crumbles|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=Voice Of America}}</ref>\n\n==Discrimination and xenophobia==\n{{main|Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThere have been increased reports of [[racism]] against Asian people, particularly against Chinese people in Europe and the Americas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Has coronavirus prompted rise in racist incidents across Europe? |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3052961/has-coronavirus-prompted-rise-racist-incidents-across-europe |work=South China Morning Post |date=29 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The coronavirus spreads racism against\u2014and among\u2014ethnic Chinese |url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/17/the-coronavirus-spreads-racism-against-and-among-ethnic-chinese |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Economist}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burton |first1=Nylah |title=The coronavirus exposes the history of racism and \"cleanliness\" |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/7/21126758/coronavirus-xenophobia-racism-china-asians |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Vox |date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \nThe [[World Health Organization]]'s Emergency Committee issued a statement advising all countries to be mindful of the \"principles of Article 3 of the IHR (the [[International Health Regulations]]),\" which the WHO says is a caution against \"actions that promote stigma or discrimination,\" when conducting national response measures to the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|website=WHO|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131005904/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Washington Post staff photographer captured a snapshot of US President Donald Trump's speech notes in which he had crossed out the word \"coronavirus\" and replaced it with the words \"Chinese virus.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/20/politics/donald-trump-china-virus-coronavirus/index.html|title=Yes, of course Donald Trump is calling coronavirus the 'China virus' for political reasons|last=Editor-at-large|first=Analysis by Chris Cillizza, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"Botsford\"/> Trump referred to coronavirus as \"Chinese virus\" in his speeches amidst growing protests of racism from different quarters. However, he stated that he does not believe his statements were racist because the virus originated there, and he also stated that he was intending to counter Chinese propaganda which claimed that American soldiers originally brought the virus to China.<ref name=\"Botsford\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jabinbotsford/status/1240701140141879298|title=Close up of President @realDonaldTrump notes is seen where he crossed out \"Corona\" and replaced it with \"Chinese\" Virus as he speaks with his coronavirus task force today at the White House. #trump #trumpnotespic.twitter.com/kVw9yrPPeJ|last=Botsford|first=Jabin|date=2020-03-19|website=@jabinbotsford|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/latest-news/it-comes-from-china-trump-hits-chinese-for-blaming-coronavirus-on-american-soldiers/|title='It Comes From China': Trump Hits Chinese for Blaming Coronavirus on American Soldiers|date=2020-03-18|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \n\nIndia has seen many cases of people from its north-east parts being called 'coronavirus' because of their racial similarities to the people of China, the country where the pandemic originated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-outbreak-in-india-northeast-racial-targeting-delhi-1657276-2020-03-19|title=Being called corona: People from Northeast allege racial targeting in Delhi|last=DelhiMarch 19|first=Ankit Yadav New|last2=March 19|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:45}}</ref> This is in the backdrop of existing problems of racism that people from these regions continue to face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/02/voices-from-india-northeast-201421811314600858.html|title=India's northeast speaks out against racism|last=Das|first=Bijoyeta|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Indian government's Minister for State for Minority Affairs, [[Kiren Rijiju]] made a statement against the increasing instances of racist comments against the people of North-east India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/kiren-rijuju-calls-out-increasing-racist-abuse-against-northeast-indians-in-wake-of-coronavirus-2541309.html|title=Kiren Rijuju Calls Out Increasing Racist Abuse Against Northeast Indians in Wake of Coronavirus|date=2020-03-18|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Suppression of information==\nAmnesty International reports that the Chinese government has censored numerous articles related to coronavirus pandemic in China. Nicholas Bequelin, Regional Director at Amnesty International has criticized that \"the Chinese authorities risk withholding information that could help the medical community tackle the coronavirus and help people protect themselves from being exposed to it\".<ref name = amnesty7/>\n\n==Harassment and intimidation==\nActivists sharing information about the coronavirus pandemic situation in China were intimidated and harassed.<ref>{{cite news |title=He filmed corpses of coronavirus victims in China. Then the police broke into his home |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-03/china-wuhan-coronavirus-censorship |work=Los Angeles Times |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"amnesty7\"/> In the United States, the Justice Department has quietly asked Congress for the ability to ask chief judges to detain people indefinitely without trial during emergencies \u2014 part of a push for new powers that comes as the novel coronavirus spreads throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swan |first1=Betsy Woodruff |title=DOJ seeks new emergency powers amid coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/21/doj-coronavirus-emergency-powers-140023 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Disproportionate border control and quarantine==\nThe Australian government sent hundreds of Australians to an immigration detention centre on [[Christmas island]], where the conditions were previously described as \"inhumane\" by the [[Australian Medical Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Virus evacuees criticise Australia quarantine plan |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-51317760 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=31 January 2020}}</ref><ref name = amnesty7/>\n\n== Right to privacy ==\nGovernments in many countries have been conducting mass surveillance in order to carry out contact tracing of the disease spread and its carriers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Governments Should Respect Rights in COVID-19 Surveillance |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/04/02/governments-should-respect-rights-covid-19-surveillance |website=Human Rights Watch |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=en |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> In China, government installed CCTV at the doors of quarantined individuals to ensure that they don't leave.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kharpal |first1=Arjun |title=Use of surveillance to fight coronavirus raises concerns about government power after pandemic ends |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-surveillance-used-by-governments-to-fight-pandemic-privacy-concerns.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=26 March 2020 |ref=cnbc |language=en}}</ref> Some residents in Hong Kong were made to wear a wrist-band linked to a smartphone app for alerting the authorities if the person broke quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saiidi |first1=Uptin |title=Hong Kong is putting electronic wristbands on arriving passengers to enforce coronavirus quarantine |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/18/hong-kong-uses-electronic-wristbands-to-enforce-coronavirus-quarantine.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=18 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In some parts of India, passengers were stamped with indelible ink on their hands, the date until the person should remain in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Privacy fears as India hand stamps suspected coronavirus cases |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-privacy/privacy-fears-as-india-hand-stamps-suspected-coronavirus-cases-idUSKBN21716U |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Violations in Prisons ==\nOn 10 April 2020, footage shared by [[Amnesty International]] revealed that detainees in a Cambodian prison are living in \u201cinhumane conditions.\" With at least 25 prisoners lying on the floor of a single small cell, the prison is claimed to be extremely overcrowded and violates physical distancing requirements. It has been called a \"ticking time bomb, especially during the coronavirus outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/04/cambodia-exclusive-footage-reveals-deplorable-prison-conditions/|title=Cambodia: Exclusive footage reveals deplorable prison conditions|accessdate=10 April 2020|website=Amnesty International}}</ref>\n\n==Stigmatization==\n{{main|Social stigma associated with COVID-19}}\nPeople have reported experiencing social stigma after recovering from the illness.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus recovery: I had to deal with a lot of social stigma after I healed - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-recovery-i-had-to-deal-with-a-lot-of-social-stigma-after-i-healed/articleshow/74760731.cms |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref> Some healthcare workers caring for individuals with COVID-19 have also reported experiencing mental health difficulties due to the fear of being stigmatized by their family and community.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samuel |first1=Sigal |title=Doctors and nurses are risking their mental health for us |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/3/26/21193122/coronavirus-mental-health-doctors-nurses-covid-19 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=Vox |date=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\">{{cite news | language =pl | title= Ministerstwo Zdrowia chce kontrolowa\u0107 wypowiedzi wojew\u00f3dzkich konsultant\u00f3w medycznych |trans-title = The Minister of Health wants to control voivodeship medical consultants' freedom of speech<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-26 |newspaper= [[Gazeta Wyborcza]] | url= https://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/7,173952,25823872,ministerstwo-zdrowia-chce-kontrolowac-wypowiedzi-wojewodzkich.html |accessdate=2020-03-27 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327015229/https://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/7,173952,25823872,ministerstwo-zdrowia-chce-kontrolowac-wypowiedzi-wojewodzkich.html |archivedate= 2020-03-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PortPielPoloz_fired\">{{cite web | last1 =Mielcarek | first1 =Mariusz | language =pl | title =Piel\u0119gniarki - po\u0142o\u017cna napisa\u0142a jak jest w szpitalu. Zosta\u0142a zwolniona! | trans-title =Nurses - a midwife wrote about the situation in a hospital. She was fired!<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | website =Portal Piel\u0119gniarek i Po\u0142o\u017cnych | date =2020-03-26 | url =https://www.pielegniarki.info.pl/article/view/id/10720 | accessdate =2020-03-27 | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20200327204145/https://www.pielegniarki.info.pl/article/view/id/10720 | archivedate =2020-03-27 | url-status =live | url-access =<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free --> }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/19/human-rights-dimensions-covid-19-response Human Rights Watch on COVID-19]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human rights issues during the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "During the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], human rights violations including censorship, discrimination, arbitrary detention, xenophobia were reported from different parts of the world. [[Amnesty International]] has responded that \"Human rights violations hinder, rather than facilitate, responses to public health emergencies, and undercut their efficiency.\"<ref name=\"amnesty7\">{{cite web |title=Here are seven ways the coronavirus affects human rights |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/02/explainer-seven-ways-the-coronavirus-affects-human-rights/ |website=www.amnesty.org |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The World Health Organization has stated that stay-at-home measures for slowing down the pandemic must not be done at the expense of human rights.<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 - 13 April 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19--13-april-2020 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=www.who.int |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Censorship==\n{{see also|National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic#Censorship and police responses}}\n===China===\nThe government of China enforced early censorship to suppress information about the coronavirus, and the dangers it poses to public health.<ref name=\"aljazeera\">{{cite news |title=How the coronavirus has deepened human rights abuses in China |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/cloneofcloneofcoronavirus-deepened-human-right-200312074518781.html |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref name=\"guardianchina\">{{cite news |last1=Eve |first1=Frances |title=China's reaction to the coronavirus violates human rights Frances Eve |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/02/chinas-reaction-to-the-coronavirus-outbreak-violates-human-rights |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=2 February 2020}}</ref> There were criticisms that the epidemic was allowed to spread for weeks before efforts were undertaken to contain the virus.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wuhan |first1=About The Author Da ShijiDa Shiji is the penname of a veteran journalist living in the city of |title=The Truth About \"Dramatic Action\" |url=https://chinamediaproject.org/2020/01/27/dramatic-actions/ |website=China Media Project |accessdate=13 March 2020 |date=27 January 2020}}</ref> [[Li Wenliang]], a Chinese doctor who alerted his colleagues about coronavirus was censored and then detained for \"spreading false rumors.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yu |first1=Verna |title=Senior Wuhan doctor dies from coronavirus as authorities start to 'round up' patients |url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/18/senior-wuhan-doctor-dies-from-coronavirus-as-authorities-start-to-round-up-patients |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=18 February 2020}}</ref> He succumbed to the infection and later died.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buckley |first1=Chris |last2=Myers |first2=Steven Lee |title=As New Coronavirus Spread, China's Old Habits Delayed Fight |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/01/world/asia/china-coronavirus.html |work=The New York Times |date=1 February 2020}}</ref> Amnesty International criticized that China's aggressive lobbying of the [[World Health Organization]] involved minimizing of the severity of the outbreak.<ref name=\"amnesty7\"/>\n\n\"[[Plague Inc.]]\", a mobile game that focuses on the simulation of global pandemics was banned by the [[Cyberspace Administration of China]] on the grounds that it had \"illegal content\" and was promptly removed from all Chinese digital stores. Ndemic Creations, the game developer, said that it is unclear whether this was in connection to the coronavirus outbreak but that they plan to work hard to get their game back into Chinese players hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/video-games/2020/02/28/plague-inc-removed-chinas-app-store/|title=Plague Inc removed from China App Store|last=Hume|first=Mike|date=|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Poland===\nAn experienced midwife working [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Poland|during the pandemic in a Polish hospital]] was fired after she published a report on [[Facebook]] on 18 March about the conditions of medical personnel and the hospital in relation to the pandemic. Reports came out afterwards that doctors were being forbidden from providing information to the media. On 25 March 2020, the [[Polish Ombudsman]] [[Adam Bodnar]] informed the Minister of Health that medical staff's freedom of speech and the public's right to know are guaranteed under [[:s:Constitution of the Republic of Poland/Chapter 1|Articles 2]], [[:s:Constitution of the Republic of Poland/Chapter 2|54 and 61 of the Polish Constitution]] and that firing or punishing doctors for informing the public during the pandemic could be a violation of the \"obligatory standards\".<ref name=\"PortPielPoloz_fired\" />\n\nOn 26 March, Poland's secretary of state of the Ministry of Health, {{ill|J\u00f3zefa Szczurek-\u017belazko|pl}}, published a written statement forbidding [[Voivodeships of Poland|voivodeship]] medical consultants from making statements related to the coronavirus unless they first consulted with the Ministry of Health or {{ill|G\u0142\u00f3wny Inspektorat Sanitarny|pl}} (GIS, the national health agency).<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\" /> A doctors' group, ''Porozumieniu Chirurg\u00f3w SKALPEL'', described the order as [[blackmail]] and said that it risked catastrophe.<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\" />\n\n=== Turkmenistan ===\nThe government of Turkmenistan outlawed the word \"Coronavirus\" on media. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/31/turkmenistan-government-outlaws-use-of-word-coronavirus/|title=Turkmenistan government outlaws any mention of the word \u2018coronavirus\u2019\n|date=31 March 2020|work=}}</ref>\n\n=== Social networks ===\nVarious [[social networking service|social networks]] applied anti-spam measures for content posted about SARS-CoV-2 and the pandemic. [[Facebook]] allegedly censored informative content about the virus.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Koetsier|first1=John|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/johnkoetsier/2020/03/17/facebook-deleting-coronavirus-posts-leading-to-charges-of-censorship/#29a970be5962|title=Facebook Deleting Coronavirus Posts, Leading To Charges Of Censorship|date=17 March 2020|work=Forbes|last2=|first2=}}</ref> According to users, posts about the coronavirus from reliable sources of media were blocked and hidden from other users. Facebook claimed a bug was responsible for this, but conspiracies are circulating that this was done deliberately to suppress information.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[YouTube]] demonetized several videos in which the term \"corona\" was used. The demonetization was cited under the rules of sensitive content.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.business-humanrights.org/en/youtube-reportedly-censors-videos-about-novel-coronavirus-by-removal-or-demonetization-company-says-they-fall-under-%E2%80%9Csensitive-topics%E2%80%9D|title=YouTube reportedly censors videos about novel coronavirus by removal or demonetization, company says they fall under 'sensitive topics'|date=20 March 2020|work=}}</ref>\n\n==Right to health==\nIn China, many patients had to be turned away from hospitals after hours of queuing due to the high number of ill people.<ref name=\"amnesty7\"/> Shortage of testing and treating material were reported.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Qin |first1=Amy |title=Coronavirus Pummels Wuhan, a City Short of Supplies and Overwhelmed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/02/world/asia/china-coronavirus-wuhan.html |work=The New York Times |date=2 February 2020}}</ref> \nDue to the high volume of patient inflow in Italy, doctors were forced to decide on whether or not to treat the elderly, or leave them to die.<ref name = italyhealth>{{cite news |last1=Horowitz |first1=Jason |title=Italy's Health Care System Groans Under Coronavirus \u2014 a Warning to the World |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/12/world/europe/12italy-coronavirus-health-care.html |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A photo of a nurse who collapsed due to huge workload in an Italian hospital was widely circulated as a symbol of the overwhelmed system.<ref name = italyhealth/>\n\nIn Libya, the medical situation was worsening amidst the ongoing war, where hospitals were constantly being attacked. In April 2020, the [[United Nations|UN]] humanitarian coordinator for [[Libya]], Yacoub El Hillo confirmed that 27 health facilities have been damaged and 14 close in five weeks. On April 6, UAE-backed forces of Khalifa Haftar launched a [[Grad rocket]] attack against the Al-[[Khadra'|Khadra]] General Hospital and damaged the 400-bed facility, where 300 patients, including two COVID-19 patients, were being treated. The attack was condemned as a violation of [[international humanitarian law]] by Yacoub El Hillo.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/04/1061272|title=Course of coronavirus pandemic across Libya, depends on silencing the guns|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=UN News|date=7 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/libya-war-escalates-health-care-system-crumbles|title=Libya War Escalates as Health Care System Crumbles|accessdate=7 April 2020|website=Voice Of America}}</ref>\n\n==Discrimination and xenophobia==\n{{main|Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThere have been increased reports of [[racism]] against Asian people, particularly against Chinese people in Europe and the Americas.<ref>{{cite news |title=Has coronavirus prompted rise in racist incidents across Europe? |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/3052961/has-coronavirus-prompted-rise-racist-incidents-across-europe |work=South China Morning Post |date=29 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The coronavirus spreads racism against\u2014and among\u2014ethnic Chinese |url=https://www.economist.com/china/2020/02/17/the-coronavirus-spreads-racism-against-and-among-ethnic-chinese |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The Economist}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burton |first1=Nylah |title=The coronavirus exposes the history of racism and \"cleanliness\" |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/7/21126758/coronavirus-xenophobia-racism-china-asians |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=Vox |date=7 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \nThe [[World Health Organization]]'s Emergency Committee issued a statement advising all countries to be mindful of the \"principles of Article 3 of the IHR (the [[International Health Regulations]]),\" which the WHO says is a caution against \"actions that promote stigma or discrimination,\" when conducting national response measures to the outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|website=WHO|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131005904/https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Washington Post staff photographer captured a snapshot of US President Donald Trump's speech notes in which he had crossed out the word \"coronavirus\" and replaced it with the words \"Chinese virus.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/20/politics/donald-trump-china-virus-coronavirus/index.html|title=Yes, of course Donald Trump is calling coronavirus the 'China virus' for political reasons|last=Editor-at-large|first=Analysis by Chris Cillizza, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref name=\"Botsford\"/> Trump referred to coronavirus as \"Chinese virus\" in his speeches amidst growing protests of racism from different quarters. However, he stated that he does not believe his statements were racist because the virus originated there, and he also stated that he was intending to counter Chinese propaganda which claimed that American soldiers originally brought the virus to China.<ref name=\"Botsford\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jabinbotsford/status/1240701140141879298|title=Close up of President @realDonaldTrump notes is seen where he crossed out \"Corona\" and replaced it with \"Chinese\" Virus as he speaks with his coronavirus task force today at the White House. #trump #trumpnotespic.twitter.com/kVw9yrPPeJ|last=Botsford|first=Jabin|date=2020-03-19|website=@jabinbotsford|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/latest-news/it-comes-from-china-trump-hits-chinese-for-blaming-coronavirus-on-american-soldiers/|title='It Comes From China': Trump Hits Chinese for Blaming Coronavirus on American Soldiers|date=2020-03-18|website=Washington Free Beacon|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \n\nIndia has seen many cases of people from its north-east parts being called 'coronavirus' because of their racial similarities to the people of China, the country where the pandemic originated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-outbreak-in-india-northeast-racial-targeting-delhi-1657276-2020-03-19|title=Being called corona: People from Northeast allege racial targeting in Delhi|last=DelhiMarch 19|first=Ankit Yadav New|last2=March 19|first2=2020UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:45}}</ref> This is in the backdrop of existing problems of racism that people from these regions continue to face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/02/voices-from-india-northeast-201421811314600858.html|title=India's northeast speaks out against racism|last=Das|first=Bijoyeta|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Indian government's Minister for State for Minority Affairs, [[Kiren Rijiju]] made a statement against the increasing instances of racist comments against the people of North-east India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/kiren-rijuju-calls-out-increasing-racist-abuse-against-northeast-indians-in-wake-of-coronavirus-2541309.html|title=Kiren Rijuju Calls Out Increasing Racist Abuse Against Northeast Indians in Wake of Coronavirus|date=2020-03-18|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Suppression of information==\nAmnesty International reports that the Chinese government has censored numerous articles related to coronavirus pandemic in China. Nicholas Bequelin, Regional Director at Amnesty International has criticized that \"the Chinese authorities risk withholding information that could help the medical community tackle the coronavirus and help people protect themselves from being exposed to it\".<ref name = amnesty7/>\n\n==Harassment and intimidation==\nActivists sharing information about the coronavirus pandemic situation in China were intimidated and harassed.<ref>{{cite news |title=He filmed corpses of coronavirus victims in China. Then the police broke into his home |url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-03/china-wuhan-coronavirus-censorship |work=Los Angeles Times |date=3 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"amnesty7\"/> In the United States, the Justice Department has quietly asked Congress for the ability to ask chief judges to detain people indefinitely without trial during emergencies \u2014 part of a push for new powers that comes as the novel coronavirus spreads throughout the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swan |first1=Betsy Woodruff |title=DOJ seeks new emergency powers amid coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/21/doj-coronavirus-emergency-powers-140023 |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Disproportionate border control and quarantine==\nThe Australian government sent hundreds of Australians to an immigration detention centre on [[Christmas island]], where the conditions were previously described as \"inhumane\" by the [[Australian Medical Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Virus evacuees criticise Australia quarantine plan |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-51317760 |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=31 January 2020}}</ref><ref name = amnesty7/>\n\n== Right to privacy ==\nGovernments in many countries have been conducting mass surveillance in order to carry out contact tracing of the disease spread and its carriers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Governments Should Respect Rights in COVID-19 Surveillance |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/04/02/governments-should-respect-rights-covid-19-surveillance |website=Human Rights Watch |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=en |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> In China, government installed CCTV at the doors of quarantined individuals to ensure that they don't leave.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kharpal |first1=Arjun |title=Use of surveillance to fight coronavirus raises concerns about government power after pandemic ends |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/27/coronavirus-surveillance-used-by-governments-to-fight-pandemic-privacy-concerns.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=26 March 2020 |ref=cnbc |language=en}}</ref> Some residents in Hong Kong were made to wear a wrist-band linked to a smartphone app for alerting the authorities if the person broke quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Saiidi |first1=Uptin |title=Hong Kong is putting electronic wristbands on arriving passengers to enforce coronavirus quarantine |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/18/hong-kong-uses-electronic-wristbands-to-enforce-coronavirus-quarantine.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=18 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> In some parts of India, passengers were stamped with indelible ink on their hands, the date until the person should remain in quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Privacy fears as India hand stamps suspected coronavirus cases |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-privacy/privacy-fears-as-india-hand-stamps-suspected-coronavirus-cases-idUSKBN21716U |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Violations in Prisons ==\nOn 10 April 2020, footage shared by [[Amnesty International]] revealed that detainees in a Cambodian prison are living in \u201cinhumane conditions.\" With at least 25 prisoners lying on the floor of a single small cell, the prison is claimed to be extremely overcrowded and violates physical distancing requirements. It has been called a \"ticking time bomb, especially during the coronavirus outbreak.\"<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2020/04/cambodia-exclusive-footage-reveals-deplorable-prison-conditions/|title=Cambodia: Exclusive footage reveals deplorable prison conditions|accessdate=10 April 2020|website=Amnesty International}}</ref>\n\n==Stigmatization==\n{{main|Social stigma associated with COVID-19}}\nPeople have reported experiencing social stigma after recovering from the illness.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus recovery: I had to deal with a lot of social stigma after I healed - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-recovery-i-had-to-deal-with-a-lot-of-social-stigma-after-i-healed/articleshow/74760731.cms |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref> Some healthcare workers caring for individuals with COVID-19 experience are mental health difficulties due to the fear of being stigmatized by their family and community.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samuel |first1=Sigal |title=Doctors and nurses are risking their mental health for us |url=https://www.vox.com/future-perfect/2020/3/26/21193122/coronavirus-mental-health-doctors-nurses-covid-19 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=Vox |date=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of major events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"GazWyb_MOH_to_censor_medicos\">{{cite news | language =pl | title= Ministerstwo Zdrowia chce kontrolowa\u0107 wypowiedzi wojew\u00f3dzkich konsultant\u00f3w medycznych |trans-title = The Minister of Health wants to control voivodeship medical consultants' freedom of speech<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-26 |newspaper= [[Gazeta Wyborcza]] | url= https://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/7,173952,25823872,ministerstwo-zdrowia-chce-kontrolowac-wypowiedzi-wojewodzkich.html |accessdate=2020-03-27 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200327015229/https://wiadomosci.gazeta.pl/wiadomosci/7,173952,25823872,ministerstwo-zdrowia-chce-kontrolowac-wypowiedzi-wojewodzkich.html |archivedate= 2020-03-27 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"PortPielPoloz_fired\">{{cite web | last1 =Mielcarek | first1 =Mariusz | language =pl | title =Piel\u0119gniarki - po\u0142o\u017cna napisa\u0142a jak jest w szpitalu. Zosta\u0142a zwolniona! | trans-title =Nurses - a midwife wrote about the situation in a hospital. She was fired!<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | website =Portal Piel\u0119gniarek i Po\u0142o\u017cnych | date =2020-03-26 | url =https://www.pielegniarki.info.pl/article/view/id/10720 | accessdate =2020-03-27 | archiveurl =https://archive.today/20200327204145/https://www.pielegniarki.info.pl/article/view/id/10720 | archivedate =2020-03-27 | url-status =live | url-access =<!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free --> }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/19/human-rights-dimensions-covid-19-response Human Rights Watch on COVID-19]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human rights issues during the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[Category:Human rights abuses]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "LopezJayLo98", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_rights_issues_during_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic"}
{"title_page": "Rashid Askari", "text_new": "{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi writer and academic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari\n| native_name         = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\n| image               = Rashid Askari.jpg\n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|06|01}}\n| birth_place         = Askarpur, [[Mithapukur]], [[Rangpur District|Rangpur]], [[East Pakistan]], Present day [[Bangladesh]]\n| office              = [[Vice-Chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh]]\n| term_start          = 21 August 2016\n| nationality         = Bangladeshi\n| occupation          = Writer, fictionist, columnist, university academic, media personality\n| alma_mater          = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Dhaka]]|[[University of Pune]]}}\n| signature           = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\u09b0 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09b0.png\n}}\n\n'''Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari''' (born 1 June 1965), known as '''Rashid Askari''', is a Bengali-English writer, fictionist, columnist, translator, media personality and an academic in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://themissingslate.com/2015/10/01/a-brief-history-of-bangladeshi-writing-in-english/2/| title= A brief history of Bangladeshi writing in English| publisher=The Missing Slate | date=1 October 2015 | accessdate= 9 July 2017}}</ref> He is the current and the 12th [[vice-chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh]] in [[Kushtia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newagebd.net/247604/rashid-askari-made-iu-vc/ | title=Rashid Askari made IU VC | publisher=New Age | date=22 August 2016 | accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAskari was born in Askarpur, [[Mithapukur]], [[Rangpur District|Rangpur]] in erstwhile East Pakistan (now Bangladesh) in 1965 to M. A. Mannan, an English teacher and headmaster, and Setara Begum, a housewife. Rashid passed the secondary school and higher secondary certificate examinations in 1980 and 1982 with merit. He \"obtained Honours and Master\u2019s degrees in English from [[Dhaka University]] with distinction, and a PhD in [[Indian English Literature]] from the [[University of Poona]]\".<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\">{{cite news |title=A Talk with IU VC |url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |newspaper=Daily Sun |location=Dhaka |date=18 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306035353/http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |archive-date=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAskari joined [[Islamic University, Bangladesh|Islamic University]], Kushtia as a lecturer in English in 1990. He became a professor in 2005 and was head of the English department more than once. He served with King Khalid University - the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia as a professor of English for five years (2008-2013). Askari later became a writer. His \"debut as a writer was marked in 1996 by his book The Dying Homeland. Until recently, he has authored seven books, and edited three volumes of English Writings of Rabindranath Tagore (2012-2013) published in commemoration of the 150th birth anniversary of the poet. He has also written a large number of articles, essays and newspaper columns on a great variety of themes ranging from national to international and colonial to postcolonial, which have been published at home and abroad\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He was elected the Secretary General of Federation of Bangladesh University Teachers' Association for 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Farid made president, Rashid secy gen of FBUTA |url=http://old-archives.newagebd.net/detail.php?date=2014-03-09&nid=86011 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=9 March 2014}}</ref> He was \"made new chairman of Folklore Studies Department of the university in [[Kushtia District|Kushtia]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=IU Folklore Dept gets new chairman|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2016/01/21/11828|newspaper=The Financial Express|location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> Askari has been nominated as a part-time member of the University Grants Commission of Bangladesh (UGC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/434781/Dr-Rashid-Askari-nominated-UGC-parttime-member|title=Dr Rashid Askari nominated UGC part-time member|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> He is working as a member of \"the international publication and translation sub-committee\" under \"Bangabandhu\u2019s Birth Centenary Celebration National Implementation Committee\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bssnews.net/?p=283009|title=Coffee table book to be published on Bangabandhu {{!}} Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS)|last=Mosharrof|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> and translated Sheikh Mujib's 10 January speech delivered at the Race Course into English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/bangabandhus-homecoming-day/news/we-dont-know-defeat-1852090|title='We don't know defeat'|date=2020-01-10|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nHe is a peer reviewer and a Quality Assurance (QA) expert nominated by the Quality Assurance Unit of the Government of [[Bangladesh|People's Republic of Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |title=Peer Reviewers Panel (QA experts) |website=Quality Assurance Unit, University Grants Commission |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020121/http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |archive-date=21 September 2016}}</ref> \"...Askari regularly writes columns in various newspapers\"...<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\" /> \"The areas of his academic interest include Modern and Postmodern Fiction, Colonial and Postcolonial Literatures, South-Asian Writing in English, Literary Theories and Creative Writing\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.sangatreview.org/rashid-askari/ | title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review}}</ref> In the recent past \"Askari has been accorded gold medal for his contribution to advancement of education sector\" in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/385380|title=Abul Hossain, Askari awarded for contribution to education sector|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/173438/?regenerate|title=IU VC got PBA gold medal {{!}} The Asian Age Online, Bangladesh|website=The Asian Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> He has also received \"Janonetri Sheikh Hasina Award 2019\" for his outstanding contribution to education sector,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/427995/IU-VC-awarded-\u2018Jononetri-Sheikh-Hasina-Sommanona-Padak2019\u2019|title=IU VC awarded 'Jononetri Sheikh Hasina Sommanona Padak-2019'|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>  and \"won the Dhaka University Alumni News Award 2020\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unb.com.bd/category/Bangladesh/iu-vc-wins-du-alumni-news-award/44638|title=IU VC wins DU Alumni News Award|last=Developer)|first=Md Ashequl Morsalin Ibne Kamal(Team Leader){{!}} Niloy Saha(Sr Web Developer){{!}} Shohana Afroz(Web Developer){{!}} Jobayer Hossain(Web|website=unb.com.bd|language=English|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>   \n\n==Writing style==\n\nAskari had a flair for creative writing since his school days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> An unsigned profile in ''The Kushtia Times'' stated that Askari writes \"both Bengali and English with equal ease and efficiency\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile of the week--Dr. Rashid Askari: Fiction writer, critic, columnist, teacher, and social analyst |url=http://www.thekushtiatimes.com/09/01/2012/profile-of-the-week/ |newspaper=The Kushtia Times |date=9 January 2012}}</ref> Bangladeshi novelist and critic [[Syed Manzoorul Islam]] notes: \"He writes witty, racy stories with surprisingly serious undertones. Picking real-life events from the remote areas and the marginal people of the country and weaving them into various fictional forms are the hallmarks of his storytelling. ... Though not new in a ground-breaking way, his stories are both intense and original. The overall tone of his language is gently sarcastic ...\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Islam |first=Syed Manzoorul |authorlink=Syed Manzoorul Islam |date=16 February 2012 |title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories: a collection of short stories |url=http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |newspaper=Dhaka Courier |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523232442/http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |archive-date=23 May 2013}}</ref> \"Dr. Askari has demonstrated enough artistic talent to come up with fiction in English, which must be a source of inspiration for many of us\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC/2016-09-18|title=A Talk with IU VC|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In his short story collection ''Nineteen Seventy One and Other Stories''(2011) \"Rashid Askari speaks of a long-ago war, revisiting the age of brutality we emerged free of through beating back the denizens of darkness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/op-ed/2019/08/22/a-chronicler-of-the-human-soul?fbclid=IwAR05ybsYp1fZgPL_slBomUp0ifBBZvZsLx4CIqHWzZpH6dwOq9V5pwAgubI|title=A chronicler of the human soul|date=2019-08-22|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The book has been translated into [[French language|French Language]] and also into [[Hindi]]\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangladeshpost.net/iu-vcs-book-translated-into-french|title=IU VC's book translated into French|last=Desk|first=BD Post|date=2018-12-01|website=A Daily with a Difference {{!}} Latest Online English Daily among Bangladesh Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>.''' ''His story \"''The Disclosure''\"'' was published in the emerging and seasoned writers publishing platform Kitaab'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kitaab.org/2019/10/12/short-story-the-disclosure/|title=Short Story: The Disclosure|last=Chakravarty|first=Mitali|date=2019-10-12|website=kitaab|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Another story \"The virgin whore\" was published in  the [[New York City|New York]] City and [[India]] based magazine Cafe Dissensus''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/03/31/short-story-the-virgin-whore/|title=Short Story: The virgin whore|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-03-31|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>''. His short story \"Virus''\"'' was published in the Daily Sun's Eid Special 2017 and \u201cA slice of sky\u201d has been published in the Contemporary Literary Review India (CLRI), a peer-reviewed , internationally refereed and high impact factor journal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Askari|first=Dr Rashid|date=2019-11-05|title=A Slice of Sky|url=https://literaryjournal.in/index.php/clri/article/view/385|journal=Contemporary Literary Review India|language=en|volume=6|issue=4|pages=68\u201391|issn=2394-6075}}</ref> \"Sharp and minute detailed description of human behaviour, and pictorial presentation of events and settings in his carefully chosen words demonstrate Rashid Askari\u2019s mastery in story writing/telling,\" says the President of the International Consortium for Social Development and Professor of Social Work at Charles Sturt University, NSW, Australia, Dr. Manohar Pawar.'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pawar|first=Manohar|date=2019-12-01|title=Askari Rashid, Nineteen Seventy One: Short Stories.|journal=The International Journal of Community and Social Development|language=en|volume=1|issue=4|pages=357\u2013358|doi=10.1177/2516602619889245|issn=2516-6026|doi-access=free}}</ref>'''\n\n==Bibliography==\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |year=1996 |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09c1\u09ae\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09c1 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 |trans-title=The Dying Homeland |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}  \n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1996 | script-title=bn:\u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cb-\u0987\u0982\u09b0\u09c7\u099c\u09bf \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u0985\u09a8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af|trans-title= Indo-English Literature and Others|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1997 |script-title=bn:\u098f\u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09c2\u09aa\u0995\u09a5\u09be|trans-title=Today's Folktale|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2001 |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4 \u09ad\u09be\u09ac\u09a8\u09be |trans-title=Deconstructing Thoughts |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2002 |script-title=bn:\u0989\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09b0\u09be\u09a7\u09c1\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09b2\u09cb\u099a\u09a8\u09be \u09a4\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac |trans-title=Postmodern Literary and Critical Theory |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2010 |title=The Wounded Land: Peoples, Politics, Culture, Literature, Liberation War, War Crimes, and Militancy in Bangladesh |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |oclc=708243896}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2011 |title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories: a collection of short stories |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |isbn=978-9848866436}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2012\u201313 |title= English Writings of Tagore(3 volumes) |location=Dhaka |publisher=Pathak Shamabesh |language=English|isbn=978-984-8866-40-5}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2018 |title=1971 Aur Anya Kahaniyan: Hindi translation of short story collection |location=New Delhi |publisher= Bhashak an imprint of Rubric Publishing |isbn=978-81935295-7-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2018 |title=Les CONTES D\u00e9chirants De 1971: French translation of short story collection |location=New Delhi |publisher= Rubric Publishing |isbn=9788193831281}}\n\n=== Short stories ===\n* \u2014\u2014 (3 August 2011). {{cite journal |last= |first= |date= |title=Lottery |url=http://www.contemporaryliteraryreviewindia.com/2011/08/lottery-short-story-by-dr-rashid-askari.html |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages= |issn= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023060908/http://www.contemporaryliteraryreviewindia.com/2011/08/lottery-short-story-by-dr-rashid-askari.html |archive-date=23 October 2013|via=}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=December 2011 |title=Nineteen seventy one |url=http://www.jpcs.in/upload/756969896Nineteen%20seventy%20one.pdf |journal=Journal of Postcolonial Cultures and Societies |publisher=Wright State University |volume=2 |issue=4 |pages=118\u2013122 |issn=1948-1845}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=January 2012 |title=Jihad |url= |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages=15\u201318 |issn=2250-3366 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=June 2012 |title=Locked-in Syndrome |url=http://issuu.com/khurshid_alam/docs/clrijun2012 |journal=Contemporary Literary Review India |volume= |issue= |pages=33\u201340 |issn=2250-3366}}\n*\u2014\u2014 (12 October, 2019) ''\"''The Disclosure''\"'' .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kitaab.org/2019/10/12/short-story-the-disclosure/|title=Short Story: The Disclosure|last=Chakravarty|first=Mitali|date=2019-10-12|website=kitaab|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*\u2014\u2014 (31 March, 2019) \"The virgin whore\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/03/31/short-story-the-virgin-whore/|title=Short Story: The virgin whore|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-03-31|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n*\u2014\u2014 (2017) \"Virus''\"'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/236318/Virus/2017-06-25|title=Virus|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>.\n*\u2014\u2014(November 2019) \u201cA slice of sky\u201d<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Askari|first=Dr Rashid|date=2019-11-05|title=A Slice of Sky|url=https://literaryjournal.in/index.php/clri/article/view/385|journal=Contemporary Literary Review India|language=en|volume=6|issue=4|pages=68\u201391|issn=2394-6075}}</ref>\n\n=== Articles ===\n* {{cite journal |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=December 2011 |title=Future of literature: Global Art-Malady and its Consequences |url=http://litsearch.co.in/Volume%201%20No.%201/1-4.pdf |journal=Litsearch |publisher=M. A. Hafiz Siddiqui |volume=1 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20134 |issn=2277-6990}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=15 December 2007 |title=War crime and the criminal |url=http://www.bt.com.bn/node/28066/print |newspaper=The Brunei Times}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=14 March 2012 |title=Eve-teasing in Bangladesh: Crime and punishment |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/14/eve-teasing-in-bangladesh-crime-and-punishment/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315201627/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/14/eve-teasing-in-bangladesh-crime-and-punishment/ |archive-date=15 March 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=14 March 2012 |title=Psychological torture on women and the legal cure |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/17/psychological-torture-on%C2%A0women-and-the-legal-cure/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318174240/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/03/17/psychological-torture-on%C2%A0women-and-the-legal-cure/ |archive-date=18 March 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=10 April 2012 |title=Population explosion and the fate of mankind |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/04/10/population-explosion-and-the-fate-of-mankind-by-dr-rashid-askari/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422120955/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/04/10/population-explosion-and-the-fate-of-mankind-by-dr-rashid-askari/ |archive-date=22 April 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=10 May 2012 |title=Bangladesh's conquest of the sea: a daunting prospect |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/05/10/bangladeshs-conquest-of-the-sea-a-daunting-prospect/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120629114321/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2012/05/10/bangladeshs-conquest-of-the-sea-a-daunting-prospect/ |archive-date=29 June 2012}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=17 February 2013 |title=Historic 21 February and the birth of a nation |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/02/17/historic-21st-february-and-the-birth-of-nation-by-rashid-askari/ |newspaper=African Herald Express}}\n* {{cite news |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |date=5 May 2013 |title=The biggest industrial disaster in Bangladesh |url=http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/05/05/the-biggest-industrial-disaster-in-bangladesh-by-dr-rashid-askari-2/ |newspaper=African Herald Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615080512/http://africanheraldexpress.com/blog7/2013/05/05/the-biggest-industrial-disaster-in-bangladesh-by-dr-rashid-askari-2/ |archive-date=15 June 2013}}\n*\u2014\u2014 ( January 2012). \"Tipaimukh Dam and Indian Hydropolitics\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.thedailystar.net/forum/2012/January/tipaimukh.htm?fbclid=IwAR3SFbUl-UdrRJ7BR_L-aAH89VSkoCKXeQuxJSLYqnqFcUvRe7wkYJK8MQY|title=Forum|website=archive.thedailystar.net|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Newspaper columns ==\n*-- (28 February, 2018). \"Bangla Should Be a UN Language\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/291923/Bangla-Should-Be-a-UN-Language|title=Bangla Should Be a UN Language|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n\n* ''--'' (13th February, 2018). \"Valentine\u2019s Day and an Anatomy of Love\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/post/288819/Valentine\u2019s-Day-and-an-Anatomy-of-Love|title=Valentine\u2019s Day and an Anatomy of Love|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n*-- (3 November, 2018). \"Dhaka Translation Fest: A Window on the World\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/347490/Dhaka-Translation-Fest:-A-%0AWindow-on-the-World|title=Dhaka Translation Fest: A Window on the World|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n*-- (24 October, 2018). \"Rabindranath, Bangladesh and the Bangalee Diaspora\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/345286/Rabindranath-Bangladesh-and-the-Bangalee-Diaspora|title=Rabindranath, Bangladesh and the Ba